{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"90923529-a8c2-4b8c-b769-29e2b5c0bccd","content":"PID 12345 isn't running on this machine, so I can't inspect it directly. Here's how to do both steps on your target machine:\n\n## 1. Detect the Runtime\n\n```bash\n# CoreCLR loads libcoreclr.so — check for it:\ngrep -q 'libcoreclr' /proc/12345/maps && echo \"CoreCLR\" || echo \"Not CoreCLR\"\n\n# NativeAOT apps are fully self-contained — no libcoreclr.so.\n# Confirm with:\nreadelf -p .comment /proc/12345/exe 2>/dev/null | grep -i nativeaot\n```\n\n**Quick rule:** if `libcoreclr.so` appears in `/proc/<pid>/maps`, it's **CoreCLR**. If not (and the binary is statically linked), it's **NativeAOT**.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Configure Crash Dumps\n\n### If CoreCLR\n\nSet environment variables **before** launching the app:\n\n```bash\n# Enable crash dumps via the .NET runtime\nexport DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump=1\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType=4          # 4 = Full heap dump (1=Mini, 2=WithHeap, 3=Triage, 4=Full)\nexport DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName=/var/dumps/coredump.%p.%t\n\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\n### If NativeAOT\n\nNativeAOT doesn't have the `DOTNET_Dbg*` knobs. Use the **OS-level core dump** mechanism:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Allow unlimited core file size\nulimit -c unlimited\n\n# 2. Configure the kernel core pattern\necho '/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee /proc/sys/kernel/core_pattern\n\n# 3. Make it persistent across reboots\necho 'kernel.core_pattern=/var/dumps/core.%e.%p.%t' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.d/99-coredumps.conf\nsudo sysctl --system\n\nmkdir -p /var/dumps\n```\n\n> **Tip for systemd systems:** If `core_pattern` is piped to `systemd-coredump` (e.g., `|/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump …`), dumps are stored via `coredumpctl`. You can either use that or override the pattern as shown above.\n\n---\n\n### Either runtime — verify it works\n\n```bash\n# Send SIGABRT to test (will kill the process!)\nkill -6 12345\n\n# Check for the dump\nls -lh /var/dumps/\n```\n\nFor **CoreCLR** dumps, analyze with `dotnet-dump analyze <file>`. For **NativeAOT**/OS core dumps, use `lldb` or `gdb`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"914c7e6c-f0ff-4c01-a570-9803a6d5a345","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The process doesn't exist on this machine (PID 12345 isn't running here). That makes sense — the user is asking for guidance, not necessarily running the app on this exact machine. Let me give them a comprehensive guide on how to detect the runtime and configure dumps for both scenarios.","outputTokens":788,"requestId":"6094:14BF27:2F985F:3E0593:69FFE543"},"id":"cdc7058c-2a75-4e7c-97e1-0bcac74a4542","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:54:28.699Z","parentId":"a093e0a2-0ead-48ac-9ebe-e344c78e90b5"}
